he years have progressed since the last recordings of the population, Japan\u2019s population has decreased, raising concern about the future of Japan. There are many causes, such as the declining birthrates, as well as the ratio of men to women since the last measurements from the years of 2006 and 2010. According to the Japanese Health Ministry, the population is estimated to drop from its current state of 126.26 million to 86.74 million by the year 2060.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/07/health/japan-child-population-record-low-intl/index.html|title=Number of children in Japan shrinks to new record low|author=Yoko Wakatsuki and James Griffiths|website=CNN}}</ref>\n\n===Sex ratio===\n[[File:Shijo procession girls 197143581 d6ea13f0a2 o.jpg|thumb|Japanese women wearing [[kimono]]s]]\n(2006 est.)\n:at birth: 1.05 male(s)/female\n:under 15 years: 1.05 male(s)/female\n:15\u201364 years: 1.01 male(s)/female\n:65 years and over: 0.73 male(s)/female\n:total population: 0.95 male(s)/female\n\n(2010 est.)\n:at birth: 1.056 male(s)/female\n:under 15 years: 1.06 male(s)/female\n:15-64 years: 1.02 male(s)/female\n:65 years and over: 0.74 male(s)/female\n:total population: 0.95 male(s)/female\n\n===HIV/AIDS===\n{{main|HIV/AIDS in Japan}}\nAdult prevalence rate\n:less than 0.1% (2009 est.)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title = Global Health Care|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=PS0C2EuedncC|publisher = Jones & Bartlett Publishers|date = 2012-05-30|isbn = 9780763799649|language = en|first = Carol|last = Holtz|page = 46}}</ref>\n\nPeople living with HIV/AIDS\n:12,000 (2003 est.)\n:9,600 (2007 est.)\n\nDeaths\n:500 (2003 est.)\n:fewer than 100 (2009 est.)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Ethnic groups===\n{{main|Yamato people}}\n[[File:Shibuya Crossing, May 2017.jpg|thumb|Japanese people in [[Shibuya]], Tokyo]]\nNaturalized Japanese citizens and native-born Japanese nationals with multi-ethnic background are all considered to be Japanese in the population census of Japan.<ref name=\"xvq\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moj.go.jp/PRESS/090710-1/090710-1.html |title=\u5e73\u621020\u5e74\u672b\u73fe\u5728\u306b\u304a\u3051\u308b\u5916\u56fd\u4eba\u767b\u9332\u8005\u7d71\u8a08\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066(Number of Foreign residents in Japan) |publisher=Moj.go.jp |date= |accessdate=2011-11-09}}</ref>\n\n===Marital status===\n{{main|Marriage in Japan}}\n:Over 15: Never married Male 61.8%, Female 58.2%. \n:16\u201324: Never married Male 31.8%, Female 23.7%.\n:25\u201329: Never married Male 69.3%, Female 54.0%.\n:30\u201334: Never married Male 42.9%, Female 26.6% (July 2000).\n\n==Vital statistics==\nLive births, birth and death rates and overall fertility rate in Japan from 1899 to present.<ref>B.R. Mitchell. International historical statistics: Africa. Asia & Oceania 1750\u20132000.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/dyb2.htm#2001 |title=United Nations Statistics Division - Demographic and Social Statistics |website=Unstats.un.org |date= |accessdate=2017-04-17}}</ref><ref>[http://www.stat.go.jp/english/data/getujidb/index.htm#b ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221022516/http://www.stat.go.jp/English/data/getujidb/index.htm |date=2012-02-21 }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|-\n!\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"|Average population \n! style=\"width:80pt;\"|Live births\n! style=\"width:80pt;\"|Deaths\n! style=\"width:70pt;\"|Natural change\n! style=\"width:70pt;\"|Crude birth rate (per 1000)\n! style=\"width:70pt;\"|Crude death rate (per 1000)\n! style=\"width:70pt;\"|Natural change (per 1000)\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"|Total fertility rate<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/><ref>{{citation|url=https://ourworldindata.org/fertility-rate|title=Fertility Rate|author=Max Roser|date=2014|work=[[Our World In Data]], [[Gapminder Foundation]]}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"|Infant mortality rate (per 1000 births)\n! style=\"width:50pt;\"|Life expectancy<ref name=\"autogenerated1\